## Migration: `TimedExecutor` to .NET 8

### Core Breaking Change

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 5+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. The entire cancellation model must change from thread-abort to **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original Thread.Join(timeout) did
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Task.Wait() already unwraps faulted tasks as AggregateException,
        // preserving the original behavior
        return task.Result;
    }

    // Async overload — preferred in modern .NET
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forced termination** | `Thread.Abort()` killed work forcibly. `CancellationToken` is *cooperative* — the `work` delegate **must** check `token.IsCancellationRequested` or call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` in its loops. Uncooperative work will run past the timeout. |
| **`default(T)` capture race** | The original code had a subtle race: `result` could be read as `default` if the thread was aborted mid-assignment. The `Task`-based version eliminates this — `task.Result` is only read after completion. |
| **`ThreadAbortException` removal** | The `catch (ThreadAbortException) { Thread.ResetAbort(); }` block won't compile. The type still exists but is never thrown. Remove it entirely. |
| **`AggregateException` wrapping** | `Task.Wait()` and `.Result` already throw `AggregateException` on fault, so the explicit wrapping is no longer needed. If callers expect a single-layer `AggregateException`, this is preserved automatically. |
| **Thread pool vs. dedicated thread** | `Task.Run` uses the thread pool. If `work` does long-blocking I/O, it can starve the pool. For that case, use `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning`. |
| **Fire-and-forget leak** | After timeout, the cancelled `Task` may still be running in the background (unlike `Abort()` which killed it). If `work` holds resources (DB connections, file handles), it **must** observe the token to release them promptly. |

### If You Cannot Modify the Work Delegate

For legacy code where `work` can't accept a `CancellationToken`, you can isolate it in a separate **process** (not thread) — that's the only safe way to force-kill uncooperative work in modern .NET:

```csharp
// Last resort: wrap uncooperative work with a hard timeout
// that abandons (but cannot kill) the background task
public T ExecuteWithHardTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    var task = Task.Run(work);

    if (task.Wait(timeout))
        return task.Result;

    // Task is still running — it will be GC'd eventually,
    // but there is no way to abort it in .NET 8
    throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
}
```

> ⚠️ This leaks the background work. Use only as a stopgap while migrating `work` to accept `CancellationToken`.
